Output message of the LLM: ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
The underlying rule is that when you start with any number from 1 to 7 and add another number, the result will always be equal to 8. This can also be demonstrated by adding     
numbers up:                                                                                                                                                                      
                                                                                                                                                                                 
1 + 2 = 3                                                                                                                                                                        
4 + 5 = 9                                                                                                                                                                        
6 + 6 = 10                                                                                                                                                                       
                                                                                                                                                                                 
This is because each step adds an increment of 1 (from 7-1, 7+8=9, 9+9=10). The overall result will always be equal to the sum of all numbers from 1 to 25.

    else:

[Step 21: Duration 15.40 seconds| Input tokens: 128,768 | Output tokens: 170,453]

Output:
The underlying rule is that a number increases by one every time it's divided by two. In other words, if you take the number n mod 2 and divide it by 2, you get back to n when you divide it by 2 again (the next number). 

For example:
- If we add 10 repeatedly until we reach 49, we would end up with the same result - 49 / 8 = 5.23 but then return to 49 after division of 7/6 by 2 is equivalent to dividing 10 by 2 and getting 5 again.
- If we take 2 times 16 repeatedly, returning back to 16 when we divide it by 8 is still the same as taking 2 times 2^3 = 12 which then returns to 49/8 after division of 7 by 2 (we have already got 5 from the previous operation)
- We would end up returning back to 49 again when we divide 64 repeatedly, but it's still valid because 64 is indeed equal to 3 times 10. So if we take a little while more before reaching 7/2 = 3 and then do the next number by taking 5 from 8 / 4 (or any other operation) will return back to 49 after division of 64 by 2 which is equivalent to dividing 7 times 10, returning it's own factorize.
- We would end up at 49/3 when we take a little while more before reaching 8/5 = 1 and then do the next number that will yield back to 49 after division of 64 by 2 (the previous operation being 7 / 3) which is equivalent to dividing 80 % by 2.
- Thus, we can continue this pattern indefinitely without ever getting stuck with anything other than a single remainder when divided by 2.

Task 70 complete.
